I have to admit i’ve been eating a lot of sugar for quite a while now. I haven’t had a cold in 25 years and the last time I had the flu was 1973.
I am 70 and I’ve avoided cancer so far and according to my doctors have nothing wrong with my heart and my blood pressure is always excellent.
I think the bottom line is everybody’s different.
Something that’s very helpful is if your throat starts to feel a little scratchy put a zinc Lozenge in your mouth and lay down on your back, letting it melt down your throat. The coronavirus affect your lungs.
The masks help mainly because it stops you from touching your nose in your mouth. Only the large droplets can pass it on. Anything that has these droplets and you touch then you touch your nose or your mouth you can get it.
Sneeze or cough into a Kleenex and dispose of it immediately safely. If you sneeze into your elbow the germs can stay and be active for a week. Wash your hands good. Don’t sneeze or cough on people.
I was in shock a couple weeks ago when a guy was standing right by the bus driver and kept coughing next to him.
Bus driver was getting mad and I don’t blame him. These are the idiots that are going to spread it.
With homeless people everywhere if it takes a hold it’s going to endanger everybody. Specially the mentally ill ones will be coughing and spitting on everyone

snippet.textDisplay: If this kills at the same rate as the Spanish Flu, extrapolated out for the increased population (2 billion then vs. 8 billion now); and adding in things they didn't have then like almost instantaneous global travel and megacities, the death count could be in the range of 800,000,000 to 1,600,000,000 people. The good news is, Spanish flu tended to kill the young and hearty with strong immune systems; this is looking like it favors people with compromised lungs (smokers) and the elderly. In any event, saying 'we have modern medicine now' isn't valid because the hospitals are already overwhelmed and understaffed with NORMAL flu and other patients. They can't handle any more, and most of our drugs come out of China, because... capitalism, almost slave labor in that country, and lack of foresight. Look at your local hospital's, or ANY hospital's 'jobs' site and count how many dozens of pleas there are for registered nurses and other critical personnel. Most hospitals only have a few respirators and a few respiratory therapists which are needed to monitor the patients on them, and they're already in use. If you get sick, you're on your own; prepare to self treat with flu medicines and common sense, which is in short supply. If you go to the doc's or hospital, you'll just cross contaminate both yourself and everyone else there, and their families, and the community at large.
